04668nam a22006135i 9780520923522DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20012001cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209235227 a10.1525/97805209235222doi  a(DE-B1597)649139  a(OCoLC)568094060  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aUB359.G7bC59 2001eb 7aHIS0100002bisacsh04a362.86/0941/090412211 aCohen, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar Come Home :bDisabled Veterans in Britain and Germany, 1914-1939 /cDeborah Cohen; ed. by Deborah Cohen. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2001] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (297 p.) :b16 b/w photographs, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Reconciliation and Stability -- tPART I: CIVIL SOCIETY IN THE GREAT WAR'S AFTERMATH -- t1. A Voluntary Peace: British Veterans, Philanthropy, and the State -- t2. The Nation Accused: German Veterans and the State Regulation of Charity -- tPART II: THE WAR'S RETURNS -- t3. Life as a Memorial: Ex-Servicemen at the Margins of British Society -- t4. Life Reconstructed: The Reintegration of German Veterans -- tConclusion -- tAppendix (Tables 1-6) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisabled veterans were the First World War's most conspicuous legacy. Nearly eight million men in Europe returned from the First World War permanently disabled by injury or disease. In The War Come Home, Deborah Cohen offers a comparative analysis of the very different ways in which two belligerent nations--Germany and Britain--cared for their disabled.At the heart of this book is an apparent paradox. Although postwar Germany provided its disabled veterans with generous benefits, they came to despise the state that favored them. Disabled men proved susceptible to the Nazi cause. By contrast, British ex-servicemen remained loyal subjects, though they received only meager material compensation. Cohen explores the meaning of this paradox by focusing on the interplay between state agencies and private philanthropies on one hand, and the evolving relationship between disabled men and the general public on the other. Written with verve and compassion, The War Come Home describes in affecting detail disabled veterans' lives and their treatment at the hands of government agencies and private charities in Britain and Germany. Cohen's study moves from the intimate confines of veterans' homes to the offices of high-level bureaucrats; she tells of veterans' protests, of disabled men's families, and of the well-heeled philanthropists who made a cause of the war's victims. This superbly researched book provides an important new perspective on the ways in which states and societies confront the consequences of industrialized warfare.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDisabled veteranszGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aDisabled veteranszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xVeteransxCarezGermany. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xVeteransxCarezGreat Britain. 4aEurope. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aCohen, Deborah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052022008940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092352240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520923522423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520923522/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Back